The &quot;Crisis in Infinite Earths &quot; was DC's way of
jumping on Marvel's bandwagon. Marvel, then, was
believed to have found the key to infinite growth, with it's recipe of
multitudes of half-baked characters thrown at the reader at machinegun
speed and uncontrolably convoluted soapoperish plots. Crisis was DC
hammering and scissoring its characters (and their bios) into versions
compatible with Marvel's style - Or with marvel's style as DC
understood it. Unsurprisingly, they called one of Marvel's frontline
writers (John Byrne) to re-design DC's frontline character. Not too
long after that, Marvel's bubble would burst, but, by then, DC was
commited to the writing strategy and writing teams impleented with
CRISIS.   In an ATL in which DC held out, choosing to fight with its
differences instead of
adopting the competitor's stragey, DC could have
resisted until Marvel's slump, in which case, it would not have any
more motivation to copy Marvel.
</POST>
