The problem with the infinite Earths, in DC's view, was that their
main character's histories had multiplied into a mismash of possible
pasts, which as a plot device meant that any event could be explained
away as yet another earth.  DC chose a high-publicity angle in an
attempt to boost sales and try to enforce a one-universe rule which
seemed to work for Marvel.  It backfired.

<QUOTE PREVIOUSPOST="
&gt;         Upside: a lot of comics whose basis was undermined by CoIE
&gt; survive in a healthier form.
">

That may happen, but the CoIE was more of a symptom of a larger
problem (IMHO): writers had to write out plots in concordance with
management directives, which sometimes completely violated the stories
they wanted to write.

<QUOTE PREVIOUSPOST="
&gt;         I suspect it won't touch some of the problems superhero
&gt; comics have&quot; the slide into grimngritty,
">

Comics tend to follow fads, particularly successful ones.  IIRC,
stories like &quot;The Dark Knight Returns,&quot; and &quot;The Killing Joke&quot; were
successful, and because of that success they spawned a host of
imitators.  Granted, mini-series themselves started a host of
imitators which got out of hand.

<QUOTE PREVIOUSPOST="
&gt; the rise of some truly
&gt; shitty artstyles,
">

That was either a fad, or the result of talent finding work
elsewhere.   The rise of independent publishers started around that
time, and a lot of the established artistic and writing talent had
grown tired of the dictates of both Marvel and DC.

<QUOTE PREVIOUSPOST="
&gt;the inevitable decline in sales.
">

Actually, one comics retailer argued that there was no real boom in
comic's readership.  Rather, it was a result of a first issue Superman
being sold for ~$30 000 US, followed by some high prices for other #1
issues (IIRC, Bat-man #1 sold $65 000 US).  That spawned a collector's
market that boosted sales which prompted the publishers to pander to
the collecters, which glutted the market, which killed the resale
value of most of the comics, which prompted the collecters to abandon
the market.  Scott McCloud, in &quot;Reinventing Comics,&quot; had a different
explanation.

(stuff deleted)

<QUOTE PREVIOUSPOST="
&gt;         Actually, what might have been an interesting idea is to do an
&gt; Earth-naught: just as Earth 1 had all its heroes begin 25 years later
&gt; than their analogs on E2, E0 is the story of an Earth whose masks are
&gt; just starting out. That's a cleaner slate with meta connections to the
&gt; old continuities and it might allow more interesting work.
">

Perhaps a more radical method would be to allow the writers to
completely rewrite the characters every 10 years.  Even then, the OTL
quality drop was inevitable, with the rise of independent publishing.
